Navigation: ← Ch 1 | Ch 3 →

Content:

**English has ~20 vowel sounds** (more than most European languages). Organised into:

**Short Monophthongs table** — IPA | Keyword | Example words | Mouth position:
/ɪ/ — KIT — bit, sit, gym, women
/e/ — DRESS — bed, head, said, friend
/æ/ — TRAP — cat, hand, laugh (some dialects)
/ʌ/ — STRUT — cup, blood, does, love
/ɒ/ — LOT — hot, watch, was, want (RP only)
/ʊ/ — FOOT — put, book, could, wolf

**Long Monophthongs table** — IPA | Keyword | Example words | Mouth position:
/iː/ — FLEECE — see, sea, machine, field
/ɑː/ — PALM/START — car, far, bath (RP), father
/ɔː/ — THOUGHT — saw, caught, door, four, war
/uː/ — GOOSE — too, blue, through, shoe
/ɜː/ — NURSE — bird, word, heard, fur, earth

**The Schwa /ə/** — most common English vowel sound:
- Unstressed syllable reduction: about /əˈbaʊt/, banana /bəˈnɑːnə/, the /ðə/ (before consonant)
- Schwa only occurs in UNSTRESSED syllables
- Examples of schwa in different spellings: a (about), e (the), o (police), i (family), u (supply)

**Diphthongs table** — IPA | Keyword | Example words | Movement description:
/eɪ/ — FACE — day, rain, break, they, eight
/aɪ/ — PRICE — my, night, buy, tied, eye
/ɔɪ/ — CHOICE — boy, coin, noise, toy
/əʊ/ — GOAT — go, stone, know, though, soul (RP)
/aʊ/ — MOUTH — now, south, crowd, house
/ɪə/ — NEAR — here, ear, idea, beer, weird
/eə/ — SQUARE — there, fair, care, wear, they're
/ʊə/ — CURE — tour, pure, sure, poor (becoming rare)

**Vowel length and spelling patterns:**
