Content:

**English has 24 consonant phonemes.** Full reference table:
| IPA | Keyword | Example words | Place | Manner | Voiced? |
/p/ — PIG — pin, happy, cup — Bilabial — Plosive — Voiceless
/b/ — BAT — bat, able, rub — Bilabial — Plosive — Voiced
/t/ — TAN — top, butter, cat — Alveolar — Plosive — Voiceless
/d/ — DOG — dog, ladder, bad — Alveolar — Plosive — Voiced
/k/ — CAT — cat, school, pick, queen — Velar — Plosive — Voiceless
/g/ — GET — get, bigger, bag — Velar — Plosive — Voiced
/f/ — FAT — fat, phone, rough, off — Labiodental — Fricative — Voiceless
/v/ — VAT — van, of, love — Labiodental — Fricative — Voiced
/θ/ — THIN — thin, path, teeth, method — Dental — Fricative — Voiceless
/ð/ — THIS — this, the, breathe, father — Dental — Fricative — Voiced
/s/ — SIT — sit, city, pass, science — Alveolar — Fricative — Voiceless
/z/ — ZAP — zoo, is, please, xylophone — Alveolar — Fricative — Voiced
/ʃ/ — SHIP — ship, sure, machine, nation — Post-alveolar — Fricative — Voiceless
/ʒ/ — MEASURE — measure, vision, genre, beige — Post-alveolar — Fricative — Voiced
/tʃ/ — CHIP — chip, watch, nature — Post-alveolar — Affricate — Voiceless
/dʒ/ — JAM — jam, badge, soldier, giraffe — Post-alveolar — Affricate — Voiced
/m/ — MAP — map, summer, comb — Bilabial — Nasal — Voiced
/n/ — NAP — nap, sunny, know — Alveolar — Nasal — Voiced
/ŋ/ — SING — sing, think, finger — Velar — Nasal — Voiced
/l/ — LEG — leg, allow, bell — Alveolar — Lateral — Voiced
/r/ — RED — red, write, carry — Post-alveolar — Approximant — Voiced
/j/ — YES — yes, few, beauty, onion — Palatal — Approximant — Voiced
/w/ — WET — wet, one, queen — Bilabial — Approximant — Voiced
/h/ — HAT — hat, who, ahead — Glottal — Fricative — Voiceless

**Special notes for each tricky sound:**
- /θ/ vs /ð/ — both spelled "th"; /θ/ = voiceless (think, bath); /ð/ = voiced (the, this, breathe). Test: hand on throat.
- /ŋ/ — never at the start of English words; -ng and -nk spelling (sing, sink)
- /r/ — in RP non-rhotic: only pronounced before a vowel. Linking-r and intrusive-r explained.
- /h/ — sometimes silent: hour, honest, heir, ghost
- /j/ — spelled as y (yes), or part of /juː/ (new, few, beauty, use)
- /w/ — silent in wr- words (write, wrong, wrist)

**Consonant clusters:**
- English allows complex clusters: /str-/ (street), /spl-/ (splash), /-ksθs/ (sixths)
- Common clusters table: initial (str-, spr-, spl-, scr-, thr-, shr-) and final (-nd, -nt, -nk, -sts, -lts, -lps)

**Consonant spellings — irregular patterns table:**
| Sound | Spellings | Examples |
/f/ | f, ff, ph, gh | fat, off, phone, rough |
/k/ | c, k, ck, ch, qu | cat, kite, back, school, queen |
/s/ | s, c, ss, sc | sit, city, miss, science |
/dʒ/ | j, g, dge, ge | jam, giraffe, bridge, large |
/ʃ/ | sh, ti, ci, ch, s | ship, nation, special, machine, sure |
/z/ | z, s, zz, x | zoo, is, buzz, xylophone |
/n/ | n, kn, gn, pn | nap, know, gnaw, pneumonia |

**Aspiration in English:**
- /p/, /t/, /k/ are aspirated [pʰ tʰ kʰ] at the start of stressed syllables: pin [pʰɪn]
- After /s/ they are NOT aspirated: spin [spɪn] (compare pin vs spin)

