### FILE 5: `Pyrite/Temp/Linguistics/Topics/04. English Pronunciation Rules.md`

Navigation: ← Ch 3 | Ch 5 →

Content:

**Word Stress:**
- English is a stress-timed language: stressed syllables occur at roughly regular intervals
- Stressed syllables = louder, longer, clearer vowel; unstressed = shorter, often reduced to schwa
- Primary stress marked with ˈ before syllable: /ˈhæp.i/, /kəmˈpjuː.tər/
- Rules for stress placement (not always predictable but tendencies):
  - 2-syllable nouns/adjectives → usually stress on 1st syllable: TAble, HAppy, PENcil
  - 2-syllable verbs → often stress on 2nd syllable: reLAX, deCIDE, beGIN
  - Stress-shifting noun/verb pairs table: REcord/reCORD, REfund/reFUND, PROtest/proTEST, CONtent/conTENT, OBject/obJECT, PERmit/perMIT, PREsent/preSENT
  - Suffixes that attract stress: -tion/-sion/-tion (naTION), -ic (deMOcratic), -ity (realiTY), -ify (iDENtify)
  - Suffixes that don't shift stress: -ness, -ful, -less, -ly, -er, -ment

**Weak Forms:**
- Function words are reduced in connected speech
- Table of common words with strong vs weak form:
  | Word | Strong form | Weak form | Example in context |
  and | /ænd/ | /ənd/ or /ən/ | bread and butter /brɛd ən ˈbʌtər/
  the | /ðiː/ | /ðə/ | the cat /ðə kæt/ (before consonant)
  the | /ðiː/ | /ði/ | the apple /ði ˈæpəl/ (before vowel)
  to | /tuː/ | /tə/ | I want to go /aɪ wɒnt tə gəʊ/
  of | /ɒv/ | /əv/ or /ə/ | cup of tea /kʌp ə tiː/
  can | /kæn/ | /kən/ | I can do it /aɪ kən duː ɪt/
  have | /hæv/ | /həv/ or /əv/ | I should have gone
  was | /wɒz/ | /wəz/ | It was good
  for | /fɔː/ | /fə/ | waiting for a bus
  at | /æt/ | /ət/ | looking at it

**Connected Speech Processes:**
- **Assimilation**: a sound changes to become more like a neighbouring sound
  - Regressive: /ɪn/ + /k/ → /ɪŋ/ (in case → [ɪŋ keɪs])
  - Progressive: ten boys → [tem bɔɪz] (n → m before bilabial)
- **Elision**: sounds are dropped in rapid speech
  - /t/ and /d/ between consonants: next door /nɛks dɔː/, friendship /ˈfrɛnʃɪp/
  - Consonant cluster simplification: facts /fækts/ → [fæks]
- **Linking**: consonant at end of word links to vowel at start of next word
  - Linking-r (RP): far away /fɑːr əˈweɪ/ — the r is pronounced because a vowel follows
  - Intrusive-r: law and order /lɔːr ənd ˈɔːdə/ — r inserted even with no r in spelling
- **Coalescence**: two sounds merge into one across a word boundary
  - /t/ + /j/ → /tʃ/: did you /ˈdɪdʒu/, meet you /miːtʃu/
  - /d/ + /j/ → /dʒ/: would you /ˈwʊdʒu/, graduate /ˈɡrædʒuɪt/

**Silent Letters (comprehensive table):**
| Letter | When silent | Examples |
b | after m, before t | comb, thumb, debt, subtle |
c | before k | black, sick, lock |
d | in -dge | bridge, hedge, knowledge |
g | before n | gnaw, sign, foreign, gnome |
gh | after a vowel | night, light, daughter, through, eight |
h | at start of some words | hour, honest, heir, vehicle, ghost |
k | before n | knee, know, knife, knit |
l | before -f, -m, -k, -d, -v | calf, calm, walk, could, half |
n | after m at end | column, autumn, solemn, damn |
p | before n, s, t (mostly Greek origin) | pneumonia, psychology, pterodactyl |
s | in some words | island, aisle, debris |
t | in some common words | castle, listen, whistle, often, fasten |
w | before r, in some words | write, wrong, answer, sword |

**Intonation:**
- Falling tone (↘): statements, commands, wh-questions — sounds definite/finished
- Rising tone (↗): yes/no questions, listing items (all but last), showing surprise — sounds open/unfinished
- Fall-rise (↘↗): implies a reservation, "but..." — sounds cautious
- Table: Utterance type → Typical intonation → Example

