### FILE 6: `Pyrite/Temp/Linguistics/Topics/05. French Vowels.md`

Navigation: ← Ch 4 | Ch 6 →

Content:

**Overview:** French has fewer vowel sounds than English but includes sounds English lacks: front rounded vowels (/y/, /ø/, /œ/) and four nasal vowels (/ɑ̃/, /ɛ̃/, /ɔ̃/, /œ̃/).

**Oral Vowels table** — IPA | Spelling(s) | Example words | Description of mouth position:
/a/ — a, à — chat, patte, là — Open front, unrounded
/ɑ/ — â, some 'a' words — pâte, bas — Open back, unrounded (fading in modern French, merged with /a/ for many speakers)
/e/ — é, er, ez, es (monosyllables) — été, parler, chez, des — Close-mid front, unrounded; pure (no diphthong)
/ɛ/ — è, ê, ei, ai, e (in closed syllable) — fête, lait, faire, belle, avec — Open-mid front, unrounded
/i/ — i, î, y — vie, île, stylo — Close front, unrounded (like English /iː/ but shorter and purer)
/o/ — o, ô, au, eau — rose, côte, eau, beau — Close-mid back, rounded; pure (no diphthong)
/ɔ/ — o (in open syllable/before /r/) — sort, or, porte, sol — Open-mid back, rounded
/u/ — ou, oû — tout, ou, où, goût — Close back, rounded (like English /uː/ but purer, more rounded)
/y/ — u, û — tu, pur, flûte, sur — Close front, ROUNDED — NO English equivalent. Lips rounded as for /u/, tongue position as for /i/
/ø/ — eu, œu (in open syllable) — deux, feu, peu, nœud — Close-mid front, rounded — NO English equivalent
/œ/ — eu, œ (in closed syllable) — peur, sœur, heure, seul, œil — Open-mid front, rounded
/ə/ — e (unstressed, not at end of word) — le, me, ce, refaire — Schwa — often silent in rapid speech

**Nasal Vowels table** — IPA | Spellings | Example words | Notes:
/ɑ̃/ — an, am, en, em — dans, enfant, temps, chambre, vent — Most common nasal; open back, nasalised
/ɛ̃/ — in, im, ain, aim, ein, yn, ym, un*, um* — vin, pain, main, plein, brun*, un* — Open-mid front nasal (*brun and un are /œ̃/ in conservative speech, /ɛ̃/ for most modern speakers)
/ɔ̃/ — on, om — bon, pont, ombre, maison — Close-mid back nasal
/œ̃/ — un, um — un, brun, parfum — Open-mid front rounded nasal (merging with /ɛ̃/ in modern French)

> ⚠️ **Key rule:** Nasal vowels occur when n or m follows the vowel AND is NOT followed by another vowel or another n/m: bon /bɔ̃/ (nasal) BUT bonne /bɔn/ (oral — the nn causes denasalisation); vin /vɛ̃/ (nasal) BUT vigne /viɲ/ (oral)

**Front Rounded Vowels — how to pronounce them:**
- /y/ (u in French): round lips tightly as if saying /uː/, then position tongue as if saying /iː/ — the result is /y/. Examples: tu, vu, pur, rue
- /ø/ (eu in open syllable): round lips as if for /o/, tongue position as for /e/ — Examples: feu, deux, peu
- /œ/ (eu in closed syllable): round lips, tongue relaxed — Examples: peur, heure, sœur

**Accent marks and vowel sounds:**
| Accent | Name | Effect on sound | Examples |
é | acute (accent aigu) | Always /e/ — close-mid | été, café, bébé |
è | grave (accent grave) on e | Always /ɛ/ — open-mid | père, mère, après |
ê | circumflex (accent circonflexe) on e | /ɛ/ (historically marked a lost 's') | fête, bête, même |
â | circumflex on a | Historically /ɑ/ (now often /a/) | pâte, château |
î, û, ô | circumflex on i, u, o | Generally no sound change; historical marker | île, flûte, côte |
à, ù | grave on a, u | No sound change; only distinguishes words | à (to) vs a (has), où (where) vs ou (or) |
ç | cedilla | c pronounced /s/ (not /k/) before a, o, u | ça, leçon, reçu |
ë, ï, ü | diaeresis (tréma) | Vowel pronounced separately from preceding vowel | Noël, naïf, Noëlle |

**E muet (Silent E):**
- The schwa /ə/ (written as e without accent) can be silent depending on position and speech speed
- Rules: silent at end of a word (une, table, belle); may be retained in formal/slow speech or when needed for pronunciation (e.g. un cheval /œ̃ ʃval/ in fast speech, /œ̃ ʃəval/ more carefully)

