### FILE 7: `Pyrite/Temp/Linguistics/Topics/06. French Consonants and Pronunciation Rules.md`

Navigation: ← Ch 5 | Index →

Content:

**Overview:** French has 20 consonant phonemes. Most are similar to English but there are key differences: the French r (/ʁ/), the palatal nasal /ɲ/, the labio-velar /ɥ/, and crucially — many final consonants are SILENT.

**French Consonants table** — IPA | Spelling(s) | Example | Notes:
/p/ — p — père, apprendre — Like English, but NOT aspirated in French (no puff of air)
/b/ — b — bon, bébé — Like English /b/
/t/ — t, th — table, thé — Like English, but NOT aspirated; dental (tongue touches upper teeth, not alveolar ridge)
/d/ — d — dans, adieu — Dental, not aspirated; like English /d/
/k/ — c (before a/o/u), qu, k — carte, qui, kilo — NOT aspirated; like English /k/ but no aspiration
/g/ — g (before a/o/u), gu (before e/i) — garçon, guerre, golf — Like English /g/
/f/ — f, ph — faire, téléphone — Like English /f/
/v/ — v — venir, vivre — Like English /v/
/s/ — s (initial/double), c (before e/i), ç, t (in -tion) — sur, assez, cinq, garçon, nation — Like English /s/; note -tion in French = /sjɔ̃/ not /ʃən/
/z/ — s (between vowels), z — maison, zéro, rose — s between vowels = /z/
/ʃ/ — ch — chat, chercher, Charles — Like English /ʃ/ (sh); NOT like English "ch" /tʃ/
/ʒ/ — j, g (before e/i) — je, jour, geste, girafe — Like the s in English "measure"
/m/ — m — maman, même — Like English /m/
/n/ — n — non, annonce — Like English /n/
/ŋ/ — -ing (borrowed English words) — parking, camping — Only in borrowed words; otherwise /n/ or /ɲ/
/ɲ/ — gn — agneau, champagne, montagne, Espagne — Palatal nasal — like "ny" in "canyon"; NO English equivalent
/l/ — l — lune, belle, il — Like English /l/ (always clear, never dark)
/ʁ/ — r, rr — rouge, Paris, arrêt — Uvular fricative/approximant — produced at back of throat, NOT like English /r/
/w/ — ou + vowel, w — oui, Louis, wagon — Like English /w/
/ɥ/ — u + vowel — nuit, lui, nuage — Rounded palatal approximant — like /w/ but with /y/ lip rounding; NO English equivalent
/j/ — i/y + vowel, -ll- (after i) — yeux, hier, fille, vaille — Like English /j/ (yes)

**The French R (/ʁ/) — how to pronounce it:**
- Produced at the back of the throat — the uvula vibrates or the back of the tongue constricts against the uvular region
- NOT a rolled/trilled /r/ (that is Spanish or Italian)
- Closest English approximation: the sound of gargling water
- Practice words: rouge /ʁuʒ/, Paris /paʁi/, merci /mɛʁsi/, bonjour /bɔ̃ʒuʁ/

**GN = /ɲ/ (NOT /gn/):**
- champagne = /ʃɑ̃paɲ/ (NOT "shamp-ag-ne")
- montagne = /mɔ̃taɲ/, agneau = /aɲo/

**CH = /ʃ/ (NOT /tʃ/):**
- chat /ʃa/ = cat (like English "sh", NOT "ch" as in "chip")
- Exception: borrowed words — chrome /kʁɔm/, chaos /kaos/

---

**Silent Final Consonants:**
French final consonants are usually SILENT. Key rule: **CaReFuL** — the consonants C, R, F, L are often pronounced at the end of words; most others are silent.

| Consonant | Usually silent? | Exceptions (pronounced) | Examples |
s (plural, verb endings) | YES — silent | — | les amis /le zami/, vous mangez /vu mɑ̃ʒe/ |
t (verb endings, many nouns) | YES — silent | — | il mange /il mɑ̃ʒ/, et /e/, vingt /vɛ̃/ |
d (past participle -nd, etc.) | YES — silent | — | grand /ɡʁɑ̃/, pied /pje/ |
x (plurals) | YES — silent | six, dix (before noun or alone) | deux /dø/, voix /vwa/ |
p | YES — silent | — | trop /tʁo/, beaucoup /boku/ |
g (in -ing, end of words) | YES — silent | — | long /lɔ̃/, sang /sɑ̃/ |
c (end) | Often PRONOUNCED | — | avec /avɛk/, chic /ʃik/, parc /paʁk/ |
r (end, most verbs, nouns) | Often PRONOUNCED | -er infinitives are silent | mer /mɛʁ/, sur /syʁ/ BUT parler /paʁle/ |
f (end) | Often PRONOUNCED | — | neuf /nœf/, chef /ʃɛf/ |
l (end) | Often PRONOUNCED | — | seul /sœl/, journal /ʒuʁnal/ |

**Liaison (La Liaison):**
- When a normally silent final consonant IS pronounced because the next word begins with a vowel or mute h
- The consonant links to the beginning of the next word

Liaison rules:
| Type | Explanation | Examples |
Obligatory | Always liaison | les amis /le‿zami/, vous avez /vu‿zave/, ils ont /il‿zɔ̃/, un enfant /œ̃‿nɑ̃fɑ̃/ |
Obligatory | After determiners, pronouns, numbers before nouns | — |
Forbidden | After et, before aspirate h, after singular nouns, after proper nouns | et il /e il/ (NOT /e‿til/); les haricots /le aʁiko/ (NOT /le‿zaʁiko/) |
Optional | In formal/literary speech | — |

Sound changes in liaison:
- s and x become /z/: les amis /le‿zami/, deux enfants /dø‿zɑ̃fɑ̃/
- d becomes /t/: grand ami /ɡʁɑ̃‿tami/
- f becomes /v/ in neuf ans /nœ‿vɑ̃/, neuf heures /nœ‿vœʁ/

**Elision (L'Élision):**
- Dropping the final vowel of certain short words when the next word starts with a vowel or mute h
- Shown in writing with an apostrophe

| Before elision | After elision | Examples |
le | l' | l'ami, l'homme, l'eau |
la | l' | l'amie, l'heure, l'école |
je | j' | j'aime, j'ai, j'habite |
me | m' | il m'appelle, elle m'a dit |
te | t' | il t'aime, elle t'attend |
se | s' | il s'appelle, elle s'en va |
de | d' | d'accord, d'habitude |
ne | n' | n'est-ce pas?, je n'ai pas |
que | qu' | qu'est-ce que, qu'il, qu'elle |
si + il | s'il | s'il vous plaît, s'il te plaît |

**Mute h vs Aspirate h:**
- ALL French h's are phonetically silent — you never say the /h/ sound
- **Mute h (h muet)**: treated as if the word starts with a vowel → triggers liaison and elision: l'homme, les hommes /le‿zɔm/
